{"rawJson":null,"m_plot":"The film is set in Joseon period where a king tries to teach his son the way of being an eligible prince and a competent king. Confucianism is the base of Joseon kingdom but the son failed to absorb it and is involved in arts, dancing and dozing away from alcoholism. Efforts made by the king to straighten his son who had strayed from responsibilities only resulted in bitter end. The king in his late age, losing hope in his son trains his grandson to the position. The grandson excels in these aspects which makes the king happy. In a drunken fiery from all bitterness and regret the prince rushes to the palace one night to assassinate the king. But hearing conversations between his son and king led him aware of what he is doing and dropped the sword. The king who initially tries to forgive, is manipulated by some members of the palace officials and ministers into thinking that the prince is beyond reckless and not worthy of being future king. The king orders to lock the prince in a rice box till his death, on the eight day the prince dies and ceremonies are held. The king moves to a secluded place for retirement. The palace is left in care of the officials and queens. After 14 years before entering to kingship the grandson meets with his grandfather, he advises to be vigilant and act knowing the difference between emotions and principle. After the grandfather passes away the grandson who is now king honors his father at his grave and his mother as his late father honored his mother. Both the son and mother shed tears with pride.","m_cast":"Song Kang-ho as King Yeongjo | Yoo Ah-in as Crown Prince Sado | Moon Geun-young as Lady Hyegyeong | Kim Hae-sook as Queen Inwon | Park Won-sang as Hong Bong-han | Jeon Hye-jin as Yeongbin Lady Lee | Park So-dam as Lady Moon | Jin Ji-hee as Princess Hwawan | Seo Ye-ji as Queen Jeongsun | Lee Dae-yeon as Kim Sang-ro | Kang Seong-hae as Kim Han-gu | Choi Deok-moon as Hong In-han | Jung Suk-yong as Eunuch Hong |